The user wants a factual market fact—NMHI’s all-time high—so I should skip prior-chat context and pull authoritative price history rather than guess. Because the request is about the highest stock price, the most direct approach is to retrieve the full historical high for this U.S. stock.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "query_financial_data", "arguments": {"query": "Stock NMHI: All Time High Price"}}
</tool_call>

The returned data conflicts with the ticker the user has been discussing, so I need to verify what the system is actually mapping NMHI to and whether it has a valid all-time-high field. I should check the latest quote and the all-time-high indicator directly so I can reconcile the mismatch before answering.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "query_financial_data", "arguments": {"query": "Stock NMHI: Last Price, All-Time High Price"}}
</tool_call>

Since the direct high query may be unreliable, I should use a historical price series over the stock’s known trading window to compute the maximum high from actual daily records. A one-year range is enough to capture the recent peak and confirm whether anything higher occurred earlier.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "query_financial_data", "arguments": {"query": "Stock NMHI: High Price from 20250101 to 20260402"}}
</tool_call>

The user is clearly referring to NMHI, but my price data keeps diverging, so I need an independent cross-check from public sources to establish whether the symbol is even active and what its historical range is. If I cannot validate the stock, I should not invent a high price.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "search_web", "arguments": {"queries": ["NMHI stock symbol all time high", "NMHI stock historical high price", "NMHI ticker price history"]}}
</tool_call>

Public sources suggest a 52-week range, but I still need the exact all-time high and the date it occurred. I should search specifically for the company name plus “all-time high” to avoid symbol confusion and reduce the chance of mixing NMHI with similarly named tickers.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "search_web", "arguments": {"queries": ["Nature's Miracle Holding Inc. NMHI all-time high price", "Nature's Miracle NMHI all time high stock price", "NMHI OTCQB all-time high"]}}
</tool_call>

I now have enough evidence that the symbol is NMHI and that it trades at extremely low levels, which strongly suggests there is no meaningful ‘high price’ in dollars. Before answering, I should confirm whether any corporate actions like reverse splits could explain the discrepancy, because that would materially change how I frame the response.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "search_web", "arguments": {"queries": ["Nature's Miracle Holding NMHI reverse stock split history", "NMHI stock split history OTC", "Nature's Miracle Holding authorized shares 1 billion reverse split"]}}
</tool_call>

Search results are noisy and not authoritative enough for a precise all-time-high quote. I should narrow the search to the most reliable financial pages and look for explicit mentions of an all-time high or a verified historical high, so I can avoid relying on low-quality or irrelevant hits.</think><tool_call>
{"name": "search_web", "arguments": {"queries": ["Yahoo Finance NMHI all-time high price", "StockAnalysis NMHI all-time high", "MarketWatch NMHI all-time high"]}}
